--------------------------------------------------
#JS
--------------------------------------------------
Number Conversion
--------------------------------------------------
Undefined = NaN
Null = 0
true = 1
false = 0
string = spaces are removed, if empty, the result will be 0, otherwise, if it isn't a number, it will be NaN (Undefined)

Examples: 
alert( Number("123") ); // 123  
alert( Number("123z") ); // NaN (error reading a number at "z")  
alert( Number(true) );  // 1  
alert( Number(false) );  // 0  

--------------------------------------------------
Boolean Conversion
--------------------------------------------------
Values that are 0, empty, null, undefined, and NaN, become false. 
Anything else becomes true.

Examples:
alert( Boolean(0) ); // false  
alert( Boolean("hello") ); // true  
alert( Boolean("") ); // false  
alert( Boolean(1) ); // true 

--------------------------------------------------
NOTES FROM W3SCHOOLS EXERCISE: https://www.w3schools.com/jsref/jsref_type_conversion.asp
--------------------------------------------------
"0" = true: this is because it does not convert the string, it only considers it's length and so since it's not empty, it is true;
[] = true;
function(){} = true;
{} = true;
